                <h2>Who Benefits Most from Preventive PRP?</h2>
                <p>While PRP can benefit a wide range of patients, certain groups stand to gain the most from using it as a preventive measure:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Men in their 20s and 30s with early recession or thinning:</strong> This is the demographic where PRP prevention delivers the most dramatic long-term value. Starting treatment at Norwood stage 1-2 can delay or prevent progression to more advanced stages for years.</li>
                    <li><strong>Women with diffuse thinning:</strong> Female pattern hair loss tends to present as overall thinning rather than distinct bald patches, making it particularly well-suited to PRP treatment. Since women cannot safely use finasteride, PRP is often the cornerstone of their prevention plan.</li>
                    <li><strong>Patients with a strong family history:</strong> If pattern baldness runs in your family, preventive PRP can be started even before significant loss occurs, based on trichoscopy findings showing early miniaturization.</li>
                    <li><strong>Post-hair transplant patients:</strong> After a <a href="../hair-transplant-in-gurgaon">hair transplant</a>, PRP is essential for protecting the native (non-transplanted) hair surrounding the grafts. Without preventive treatment, these native hairs may continue to thin, eventually creating an unnatural contrast with the transplanted area.</li>
                    <li><strong>Patients recovering from telogen effluvium:</strong> After a period of stress-induced shedding, PRP can accelerate recovery and prevent the temporary condition from triggering a longer-term pattern of hair loss.</li>
                </ul>

                <h2>Limitations of PRP for Hair Loss Prevention</h2>
                <p>While PRP is a powerful preventive tool, it is important to understand its boundaries:</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>PRP cannot override genetics entirely.</strong> If you are genetically predisposed to significant hair loss, PRP can slow the process substantially but may not stop it indefinitely without complementary treatments like DHT blockers.</li>
                    <li><strong>Results require maintenance.</strong> PRP is not a one-time fix. The preventive benefits depend on periodic maintenance sessions, typically every 4-6 months. Stopping treatment may allow hair loss to resume its natural course.</li>
                    <li><strong>PRP cannot revive dead follicles.</strong> Once a follicle has been permanently destroyed, no amount of PRP can bring it back. This is why early intervention is so important -- once follicles are lost, the only option is surgical transplantation.</li>
                    <li><strong>Response varies between individuals.</strong> Factors such as age, the extent of miniaturization, platelet quality, overall health, and lifestyle habits all influence how well a patient responds to PRP. Approximately 15-20 percent of patients are classified as "poor responders" who may see limited benefit.</li>
                    <li><strong>PRP is not a substitute for treating underlying conditions.</strong> If hair loss is driven by thyroid dysfunction, autoimmune disease, nutritional deficiency, or medication side effects, these underlying causes must be addressed alongside PRP for optimal results.</li>
                </ul>

